    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "idk i dont think its just shade cuz the yellowing is pretty intense and honestly the soil feels kinda depleted. i was reading online that nitrogen might be the issue. if its nitrogen, how do i fix the soil ph to make sure they actually absorb it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If the yellowing is intense and you suspect nitrogen deficiency, it's possible that the soil is indeed depleted. To address this, you can add a balanced fertilizer that contains nitrogen, phosphorus, and potassium (NPK). However, if you want to adjust the soil pH to optimize nutrient absorption, you should first test the current pH level of your soil. Most tomatoes prefer a slightly acidic to neutral soil pH, around 6.0-6.8. If the pH is too high or too low, it can affect nutrient availability, but you can adjust it by adding lime to raise the pH or elemental sulfur to lower it.",
